description:
One of the issues that causes controversy between Jesus and the Pharisees over and over again is their different understanding of the Sabbath. Today weâ€™re looking at the first time this issue comes up in the gospel of Mark.

One Sabbath Jesus was going through the grainfields, and as his disciples walked along, they began to pick some heads of grain. 24 The Pharisees said to him, â€œLook, why are they doing what is unlawful on the Sabbath?â€ 25 He answered, â€œHave you never read what David did when he and his companions were hungry and in need? 26 In the days of Abiathar the high priest, he entered the house of God and ate the consecrated bread, which is lawful only for priests to eat. And he also gave some to his companions.â€ 27 Then he said to them, â€œThe Sabbath was made for man, not man for the Sabbath. 28 So the Son of Man is Lord even of the Sabbath.â€ â€“ Mark 2:23-27

One Sabbath, the disciples were hungry. So as they walked, they picked some heads of grain. They were eating them because they were hungry. The Pharisees had all kinds of human rules about what you werenâ€™t allowed to do on the Sabbath day, and they were always looking to point out anything that Jesus or his disciples did wrong.

So, they asked Jesus why was it that his disciples were breaking the law on the Sabbath. 
When Jesus responded, he didnâ€™t say that the Sabbath didnâ€™t matter. Not at all! Instead, his answer showed them that the Sabbath was very important. Jesus told the Pharisees that they didnâ€™t understand the true purpose of the Sabbath: it wasnâ€™t so that humanity should be slaves of the Sabbath, but so that the Sabbath should be a blessing and meet humanityâ€™s needs.

But then he went further. Jesus told them that he himself was the Lord of the Sabbath. 
In other words, he was the Lord, and he owned the day. The Sabbath was the Lordâ€™s Day, his special day, and human rules couldnâ€™t be used to tell him what could or couldnâ€™t be done on the Sabbath.

There are people today who say that the Sabbath doesnâ€™t matter. But Jesus said that the Sabbath has been given to us to meet the needs of humanity, to be a blessing. What are the needs that you think it meets?
